data.content:
This is a **C# 14 span overload resolution breaking change**.

## What happened

In C# 14, `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads now participate in type inference and extension method resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (a span-based method) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. 

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree, so it throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` using any of these approaches:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
